    <title>Polygonal Number Formulas</title>
    <content type='html'>&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEg9cmM_NfmLj6h_jlnlrL5JSpz2_cxKdYW2Ce2KzSreE2vEIN2NL041BlxUJ-Kk72rzocuwLEPtuh2Rg0IH-3hHxxt5kWrzxt_WCY60fI8LAm2j-K_KYVrLC9G-mFqZCZeamfTH8Kt2nlI/s1600-h/hexagonals.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEg9cmM_NfmLj6h_jlnlrL5JSpz2_cxKdYW2Ce2KzSreE2vEIN2NL041BlxUJ-Kk72rzocuwLEPtuh2Rg0IH-3hHxxt5kWrzxt_WCY60fI8LAm2j-K_KYVrLC9G-mFqZCZeamfTH8Kt2nlI/s400/hexagonals.jpg" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5233373394828257922" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt; A few of the posts on this blog have dealt with the &lt;a href="http://mathrecreation.blogspot.com/search/label/polygonal"&gt;polygonal numbers&lt;/a&gt;. Polygonal numbers are a mainstay of recreational and school mathematics, providing a nice bridge between numbers and shapes. The diagrams above (created using the instructions in &lt;a href="http://mathrecreation.blogspot.com/2008/07/drawing-polygonal-numbers.html"&gt;an earlier&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a href="http://mathrecreation.blogspot.com/2008/07/drawing-polygonal-numbers.html"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a href="http://mathrecreation.blogspot.com/2008/07/drawing-polygonal-numbers.html"&gt; post&lt;/a&gt;) show some of the hexagonal numbers.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;This post is intended to provide some (limited) background information on two-dimensional polygonal numbers. A &lt;a href="http://mathrecreation.blogspot.com/2008/07/higher-polygonal-numbers-and-pascals.html"&gt;previous post&lt;/a&gt; suggested an approach for generating a formula for higher-dimensional polygonal numbers. Future posts will elaborate on these numbers some more.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Some examples of two-dimensional polygonal numbers are:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;the triangular numbers: 1, 3, 6, 10, 15, ...&lt;br /&gt;the square numbers: 1, 4, 9, 16, 25, ...&lt;br /&gt;the pentagonal numbers: 1, 5, 12, 22, 35,...&lt;br /&gt;the hexagonal numbers: 1, 6, 15, 28, 45, ...&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Comparing the listing for the hexagonal numbers with the diagrams above, you can see how the sequences are built diagrammatically. In general, beginning with a single dot, k-sided polygons are built by adding layers (called gnomons) consisting of k-2 segments, with each segment of the gnomon having one more dot than the segments of the previous layer. In this way, the nth gnomon consists of segments each n dots long, but with k-3 dots shared by adjoining segments (the corners).&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The description above can lead you to a recursive formula for k-polygonals, writing p_k,n for the nth k-polygonal number:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjoE7cMhV8SJKZdvi-JZc8QGTxsO-UYL3zLEZTJGoKaejnbVnOLHx4Ij-IPcoW_2zo-pr3gANcJOl7eO2d-GW1TT9ApHH9iX6o4X0CmmSXm7Uihv4yo2TURRzo6ahGWo1nlsr4Y-G4dnvU/s1600-h/poly-rec-eq.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer; width: 343px; height: 48px;" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjoE7cMhV8SJKZdvi-JZc8QGTxsO-UYL3zLEZTJGoKaejnbVnOLHx4Ij-IPcoW_2zo-pr3gANcJOl7eO2d-GW1TT9ApHH9iX6o4X0CmmSXm7Uihv4yo2TURRzo6ahGWo1nlsr4Y-G4dnvU/s400/poly-rec-eq.jpg" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5233375145923926658" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Unwinding the recursion gives you a summation formula for k-polygonals:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEg1rPlhyphenhyphenFN1Q5N8jEEhGzG3IbH3O6315LAFkKz_QboI224A_kUUzgtz9967cnZIRG_C6UR8oMnD8oGQsWP3dhfn0U_doJOz-jBFAidt3cA0kbbhLs4jSwMqC5yC2txD6YR_Q0lIQv0_s3k/s1600-h/poly-sum-eq.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer; width: 236px; height: 61px;" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEg1rPlhyphenhyphenFN1Q5N8jEEhGzG3IbH3O6315LAFkKz_QboI224A_kUUzgtz9967cnZIRG_C6UR8oMnD8oGQsWP3dhfn0U_doJOz-jBFAidt3cA0kbbhLs4jSwMqC5yC2txD6YR_Q0lIQv0_s3k/s400/poly-sum-eq.jpg" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5233375364924719826" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Knowing a little about sums gives you the direct formula for k-polygonals:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEgheR3X5qk5YRHskVoh2Cl9A30KHNx0-ukGd06y_B4QP4e62SZsDem0cPZbVBaSbgqtCkhoDk55oWrC-k_WZRmOnDZ93PC0wxHj3Ny_M4k8tffHZj6mGED-eR8eFNWpbdVsu7gqHQ2E6U4/s1600-h/poly-direct-eq.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer; width: 278px; height: 66px;" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEgheR3X5qk5YRHskVoh2Cl9A30KHNx0-ukGd06y_B4QP4e62SZsDem0cPZbVBaSbgqtCkhoDk55oWrC-k_WZRmOnDZ93PC0wxHj3Ny_M4k8tffHZj6mGED-eR8eFNWpbdVsu7gqHQ2E6U4/s400/poly-direct-eq.jpg" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5233375655527246018" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Coming a little out of left-field is this combinatorial formula for k-polygonals:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEj_lJ8NeGdwAW-pKhwBSMVCevhGND6pJBha3HZ2CUoCgltin-Ea-Y0bOlckXGGhSFsLHNJO5r54Otj7zi7LVbV5Bwq37dm1E5LRpg-gm0DOU_KngD4gFAen8BCMrpfqB4Y8Z-Veq2ACM1o/s1600-h/poly-comb-eq.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer; width: 257px; height: 61px;" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEj_lJ8NeGdwAW-pKhwBSMVCevhGND6pJBha3HZ2CUoCgltin-Ea-Y0bOlckXGGhSFsLHNJO5r54Otj7zi7LVbV5Bwq37dm1E5LRpg-gm0DOU_KngD4gFAen8BCMrpfqB4Y8Z-Veq2ACM1o/s400/poly-comb-eq.jpg" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5233375853424708642" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;This last formula expresses two ideas: that the triangular numbers correspond to the r=0 column of Pascal's triangle, and that every polygonal number can be "triangulated":&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEirDxjORPpqqJjaFctUj7qau5SN_7yTFYmSTlRgEJOrQv57TFCW1a-s-UTGGVI1qrjXEqykoYcWz5x260_-YrgVYf67Xh14W8VA8f5jbo9DD1BT-NIVmi9Isb1UML0t8tizgeGSXoaHJ8U/s1600-h/triangulation.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer; width: 351px; height: 69px;" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEirDxjORPpqqJjaFctUj7qau5SN_7yTFYmSTlRgEJOrQv57TFCW1a-s-UTGGVI1qrjXEqykoYcWz5x260_-YrgVYf67Xh14W8VA8f5jbo9DD1BT-NIVmi9Isb1UML0t8tizgeGSXoaHJ8U/s400/triangulation.jpg" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5233996244300863250" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The combinatorial formula for p_kn can be generalized to higher-dimensional polygonal numbers (pyrimidal numbers, etc.). See this &lt;a href="http://mathrecreation.blogspot.com/2008/07/higher-polygonal-numbers-and-pascals.html"&gt;previous post&lt;/a&gt; for some discussion on this.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The recreation here lies in showing that the various  formulas for p_k,n are really the same, and then exploring the relationships between the different k-polygonals. A great resource is J.H. Conway and R.K. Guy's &lt;a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=cLEhHELiwrQC&amp;amp;dq=book+of+numbers+conway&amp;amp;source=gbs_summary_s&amp;amp;cad=0"&gt;The Book of Numbers&lt;/a&gt;.</content>
